<subSubSection pageId="122" pageNumber="123" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="122.[701,1228,287,990]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">
DEFINITION: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="White" baseAuthorityYear="1790" box="[892,1066,290,311]" class="Reptilia" family="Varanidae" genus="Varanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="varius">
<emphasis box="[892,1066,290,311]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Varanus varius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Lanthanotidae" genus="Lanthanotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borneensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Lanthanotus borneensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and all descendants of their last common ancestor.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="122" pageNumber="123" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="122.[701,1228,287,990]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">DIAGNOSIS: Varanids are united by 115(1) absence of palatine teeth, 118(1) pterygoid teeth arranged in a single line, 149(1) presence of an expansive crista tuberalis (see character description above), and 151(1) anterior location for the spheno-occipital tubercle.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="122" pageNumber="123" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="122.[701,1228,287,990]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">
COMMENTS: The present definition of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1827" box="[701,822,615,637]" class="Reptilia" family="Varanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Varanidae</taxonomicName>
follows that of common usage and previous phylogenetic definitions (Estes et al., 1988; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pianka, E. R." box="[855,1013,673,696]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="398 - 414" refId="ref97327" refString="Pianka, E. R. 1995. Evolution of body size: varanid lizards as a model system. American Naturalist 146: 398 - 414." type="journal article" year="1995">Pianka, 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lee, M. S. Y." box="[1028,1147,674,695]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="369 - 453" refId="ref93302" refString="Lee, M. S. Y. 1998. Convergent evolution and character correlation in burrowing reptiles: towards a resolution of squamate relationships. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 65: 369 - 453." type="journal article" year="1998">Lee, 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bernstein, P." pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="219 - 230" refId="ref83955" refString="Bernstein, P. 1999. Morphology of the nasal capsule of Heloderma suspectum with comments on the systematic position of helodermatids (Squmata: Helodermatidae). Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 80: 219 - 230." type="journal article" year="1999">Bernstein, 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Conrad, J. L." box="[852,1034,703,725]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="399 - 434" refId="ref86006" refString="Conrad, J. L. 2004 a. Skull, mandible, and hyoid of Shinisaurus crocodilurus Ahl (Squamata, Anguimorpha). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 141: 399 - 434." type="journal article" year="2004">Conrad, 2004a</bibRefCitation>
, 2006a, 2006b). The clade as defined here was left unnamed in 
<bibRefCitation author="Lee, M. S. Y." box="[738,870,762,784]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="53 - 91" refId="ref93264" refString="Lee, M. S. Y. 1997. The phylogeny of varanoid lizards and the affinities of snakes. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B Biological Sciences 352: 53 - 91." type="journal article" year="1997">Lee (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, a study in which the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1827" box="[701,822,791,813]" class="Reptilia" family="Varanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Varanidae</taxonomicName>
was defined as all taxa sharing a more recent common ancestor with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1790" box="[1132,1228,822,843]" class="Reptilia" family="Varanidae" genus="Varanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1132,1228,822,843]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Varanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than with 
<taxonomicName box="[832,1105,850,873]" class="Reptilia" family="Lanthanotidae" genus="Lanthanotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borneensis">
<emphasis box="[832,1105,850,873]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Lanthanotus borneensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Caldwell, M. W." pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="115 - 147" refId="ref85040" refString="Caldwell, M. W. 1999 a. Squamate phylogeny and the relationships of snakes and mosasauroids. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 125: 115 - 147." type="journal article" year="1999">Caldwell (1999a)</bibRefCitation>
produced a hypothesis of relationships differing from that of the current analysis (fig. 8), but that is one of the only recent studies to do so.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
